Thanks for your pull request.  It looks like this may be your first contribution to a Google open source project. Before we can look at your pull request, you'll need to sign a Contributor License Agreement (CLA).

:memo: **Please visit <https://cla.developers.google.com/> to sign.**

Once you've signed, please reply here (e.g. `I signed it!`) and we'll verify.  Thanks.

---

- If you've already signed a CLA, it's possible we don't have your GitHub username or you're using a different email address.  Check [your existing CLA data](https://cla.developers.google.com/clas) and verify that your [email is set on your git commits](https://help.github.com/articles/setting-your-email-in-git/).
- If you signed the CLA as a corporation, please let us know the company's name.

We found a Contributor License Agreement for you (the sender of this pull request), but were unable to find agreements for the commit author(s).  If you authored these, maybe you used a different email address in the git commits than was used to sign the CLA ([login here](https://cla.developers.google.com/) to double check)?  If these were authored by someone else, then they will need to sign a CLA as well, and confirm that they're okay with these being contributed to Google.

I signed it

(Trying again with the correct author)

CLAs look good, thanks!

<!-- ok -->

Thank you for making this effort, but I would recommend holding off on this for just a little while. I have a few upcoming changes that I think will make it easier to define a more complete strongly typed API definition. One of those changes that starts this off is #11031.

Didn't see that PR. Looks great. Do you have any ETA on the changes?
I'll keep running with my local version and we can see in to merge in when ever you see fit.

The changes I'm making are mainly API documentation improvements, probably with a few API improvements to make that easier. I expect them to be done within the next week or two.

I like your idea of explicitly declaring the status enum (and other similar objects) in JavaScript, and that will likely become part of the actual library.

I'd appreciate that. It was actually hard for me to locate these codes in the source.
The documentation improvements, are they code based or as an interactive (web) documentation?
Any of these are much missed and it would be great if we could get a generated documentation that is all ways up to date.

Just found http://www.grpc.io/grpc/node/
This makes my life way easier. Don't know how I missed this.
Thanks for your pull request. The automated tests will run as soon as one of the admins verifies this change is ok for us to run on our infrastructure.

Thank you @connor4312 That is some great notes. I'll get them fixed eventually.
How is the other API changes coming @murgatroid99?

The API changes I referred to have been submitted, and there have been some significant documentation updates. The primary changes make the `Client` base class a separate public API, and also move the enums that were previously implemented in C++ into the JavaScript code. The new documentation will be published soon, when we release 1.4.0.

Sounds good. I'll give it a look and if I make it in time, maybe this PR
can be merged before the 1.4 release as well?
